III. PROJECT RENAMING OBLIGATION (MANDATORY)

When you distribute a modified version of the Software as a STANDALONE PROJECT
(meaning you create a new project that is a derivative work of the original),
you MUST rename the project to a name that is clearly different from the
original project name. You are NOT permitted to use the original name,
abbreviation, logo, or any variation thereof that could cause confusion with
the original work.

EXCEPTION: If you are using the Software as a LIBRARY, PACKAGE, OR DEPENDENCY
within your own project (whether modified or unmodified), you are NOT required
to rename the library's internal package name, class names, or namespace.
The original package name (e.g., com.example.originallib) may remain unchanged.

Example 1 (Standalone Project - MUST rename):
- You fork "SuperLogger" and build a new logging application called "MegaLogger"
- You MUST rename the project, directory name, and executable name
- You MAY keep internal package names (e.g., com.superlogger.core) unchanged

Example 2 (Library Usage - NO rename required):
- You add "SuperLogger" as a dependency in your project "MyApp"
- Your project uses import com.superlogger.core.Logger
- You DO NOT need to rename the package com.superlogger.core

Example 3 (Library with modifications - NO rename required):
- You modify "SuperLogger" library to fix a bug and use it in your project
- You distribute your modified version as a library
- You DO NOT need to rename the package, but you MUST clearly indicate your
  modifications are not from the original author (e.g., in the library's README)

